node.text:
Have you ever seen amphibian eggs? 👀 ⁣
⁣
While it's never a good idea to mess with nature, I'm happy to report that these eggs were carefully put back in the water to continue growing. ⁣
⁣
These are believed to be from some species of frog, but pretty much all amphibian eggs are this way. ⁣
⁣
They lay their eggs in jelly-like masses which are then kept in water to avoid drying up (if they dry up they die). ⁣
⁣
The jelly protects them from predators and also helps to attract warmth to the eggs from the sun. ⁣
⁣
🎥: @justinnterryy
